<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n34033b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n34" href="#n34033b">N34 (VI.B.27)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n34all.htm#n34033b"> 33(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <sup>n</sup>P<sub>r</sub> &#247; r! = <sup>n</sup>C<sub>r</sub> <small>Not cancelled</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n34033b"><li>FW 284.26 </li><li><a href="../../flex/lg/lexlg.htm#n34033b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/lg/l39lg.htm#n34033b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n34033b">MS BL 47478-45</ms> </li><li>JJA 53:123 <a name="lgd8" href="../../FF/fdra/lda.htm#lgd8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/lg/lgd8.htm#n34033b">Draft: II.2&sect;8.8</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The]</font> number of combinations of n dissimilar things taken r at a time <font color="green">[is denoted by the symbol]</font> <sup>n</sup>C<sub>r</sub>. Each of these combinations consists of a group of r dissimilar things which can be arranged among themselves in &#8735;r <font color="green">[=r!]</font> ways. Hence <sup>n</sup>C<sub>r</sub> &times; &#8735;r <font color="green">[r!]</font> is equal to the number of arrangements of n things taken r at a time ; that is, <sup>n</sup>C<sub>r</sub> &times; r! = <sup>n</sup>P<sub>r</sub>. <small> Hall &amp; Knight, <a name="HSHK" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#HSHK"><cite title="source">Elementary Algebra for Schools</cite></a> (n.d) 321</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: <i>Combinations</i> do <i>not</i> take account of the order, so that <i>abcd</i> is counted as being the same as <i>acbd</i>. It follows that the number of combinations of n things taken all at a time is only one. </mm> </dd></dl>
